Instead of having to climb and search for water, families suddenly had access right next to their homes. And because it was a clean and safe water source, the health of the community transformed.

The local clinic went from seeing 700 patients per month down to 60–65. The reported number of diarrhea cases dropped from a high of more than 6,000 per year to under 200.

Today, Netra’s students will gladly tell you that they aspire to become scientists, doctors, engineers, teachers, and social workers. That they want to research health and make medicines for others. That they’re eager to embrace technology. That they want to build a better future for themselves, their families, and their community.